SIMPLE: footing
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Footing
<hw>Foot"ing</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Ground for the foot;
place for the foot to rest on; firm foundation to stand on.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>In ascent, every step gained is a <qex>footing</qex> and help to
the next.</q> <rj><qau>Holder.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Standing; position; established place; basis for
operation; permanent settlement; foothold.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>As soon as he had obtained a <qex>footing</qex> at court, the
charms of his manner . . . made him a favorite.</q>
<rj><qau>Macaulay.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Relative condition; state.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Lived on a <qex>footing</qex> of equality with nobles.</q>
<rj><qau>Macaulay.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>Tread; step; especially, measured tread.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Hark, I hear the <qex>footing</qex> of a man.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>The act of adding up a column of figures; the amount
or sum total of such a column.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <def>The act of putting a foot to anything; also, that
which is added as a foot; <as>as, the <ex>footing</ex> of a
stocking</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>7.</sn> <def>A narrow cotton lace, without figures.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>8.</sn> <def>The finer refuse part of whale blubber, not wholly
deprived of oil.</def> <rj><au>Simmonds.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>9.</sn> <fld>(Arch. & Enging.)</fld> <def>The thickened or
sloping portion of a wall, or of an embankment at its foot.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Footing course</b></col> <fld>(Arch.)</fld>, <cd>one of
the courses of masonry at the foot of a wall, broader than the courses
above.</cd> -- <col><b>To pay one's footing</b></col>, <cd>to pay a fee
on first doing anything, as working at a trade or in a shop.</cd>
<au>Wright.</au> -- <col><b>Footing beam</b></col>, <cd>the tie beam of
a roof.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Footless</ent>⟦br⟧
